WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:12.320 --> 00:00:14.040
SHANE SMITH: It turned out to
be a comparatively short

00:00:14.040 --> 00:00:17.420
10-hour train ride from Tynda to
Dipkun, which was the next

00:00:17.420 --> 00:00:21.280
town that had a North
Korean camp in it.

00:00:21.280 --> 00:00:23.660
When we finally got there, it
was pretty late in the day.

00:00:23.660 --> 00:00:24.970
We had to move fast.

00:00:24.970 --> 00:00:27.070
If we were going to see the
North Korean camp and get back

00:00:27.070 --> 00:00:30.120
in time before the pitch black
Siberian night fell and

00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:32.440
stranded us in the forest.

00:00:32.440 --> 00:00:35.450
Well, we're sort of in the
middle of nowhere.

00:00:35.450 --> 00:00:37.460
But we're going to try to
go to the camp now.

00:00:40.170 --> 00:00:42.580
The old chief of police of
Dipkun, who we met on the

00:00:42.580 --> 00:00:45.440
train, had offered to take us
out there in his new truck but

00:00:45.440 --> 00:00:47.920
was a bit worried about the
bridge because it had recently

00:00:47.920 --> 00:00:49.640
been washed out.

00:00:49.640 --> 00:00:50.510
We could take this.

00:00:50.510 --> 00:00:52.242
This would be awesome.

00:00:52.242 --> 00:00:53.492
Is this us?

00:00:56.010 --> 00:00:59.660
So we are in a race against
time to go see the North

00:00:59.660 --> 00:01:00.610
Korean camp.

00:01:00.610 --> 00:01:03.680
The old chief of police
is driving us.

00:01:07.150 --> 00:01:09.670
He'd been the chief of police
for over a decade and

00:01:09.670 --> 00:01:11.000
consequently knew
the North Korean

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:12.360
situation there quite well.

